  "prompt": "Why do Navy squadrons start with a V?",
  "response": "In naval aviation, squadrons traditionally begin with the letter \"V\" to designate them as fixed-wing aircraft squadrons. This designation stands for \"heavier-than-air\" (from the French \"vol\" meaning flight) and distinguishes them from lighter-than-air squadrons. Helicopter squadrons typically start with \"H\" and other specialized aviation units have their own prefixes. This naming convention has been used by the U.S. Navy for many decades as a standard way of identifying different types of aviation units.",
